##DESCRIPTION
##KEYWORDS('pigeon hole principle')
##problem 4 section 4.2 of Discrete Math by Kenneth Rosen
##this problem is also located in the directory setProbability1Combinations
##ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$a=random(5,10,1);
$b=$a+3;

BEGIN_TEXT

A bowl contains \( $a \) red balls and \( $a \) blue balls. A woman 
selects balls at random without looking at them. $BR
(a) How many balls must she select (minimum) to be sure of having 
at least three blue balls?
\{ ans_rule(10) \}
$PAR
(b) How many balls must she select (minimum) to be sure of having 
at least three balls of the same color?
\{ ans_rule(10) \}
$PAR
END_TEXT

ANS(num_cmp( $b ) );
ANS(num_cmp( 5 ) );


ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.;
